# No hard-coded fallbacks

Do NOT embed hard-coded copies of data that has an authoritative external source
(config files, data files, plugin records, APIs). A hard-coded fallback that
mirrors the real source **silently masks failures** — the code looks data-driven
while actually running on stale, baked-in values.

This burned a sibling project: a `UseBuiltinPositionFallback()` hard-coded the same
ids as its `Positions.txt`, so a failed file read was invisible — impossible to
tell whether the mod was reading the file or the copy.

## Rules

- If a required source can't be read, **fail loudly** (error log + user-visible
  notification), do not substitute look-alike data.
- A "safety default" may exist only if it is **minimal and obviously distinct**
  from the real data (e.g. a single clearly-labeled placeholder), never a full
  mirror of the source.
- Never keep the same list/values in both code and a file (see
  `single-source-of-truth`).

## Example

```papyrus
; BAD — hidden mirror of a data file; a broken read looks identical to success
Function UseBuiltinFallback()
    Lines[0] = "some value that also lives in the file"
    ; ...more identical to the file...
EndFunction

; GOOD — the file is the source; a failure is impossible to miss
If !GardenOfEden.DoesFileExist(FILE, PATH)
    Debug.Notification("PickmansWhisper: <file> NOT FOUND — nothing loaded")
    Debug.Trace("PickmansWhisper: ERROR <file> missing at " + PATH)
    Return
EndIf
```

A silent fallback that copies the source is worse than an honest error.
